<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-568-386  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 568 386.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  May 1990 v37 n5 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How to manage automation projects.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Trudel, David T.; Goodwin, Craig R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-integrated manufacturing (CIM) can provide plant wideefficiency, improved quality, and improved productivity.andO;Automation of the process is the first step in accomplishing thesegoals and automating the process will mean integratingmulti-vendor control systems.andP;  The steps in implementing amulti-vendor automated production process are: developmentstrategy, establishing system architecture, system design andspecification, communications, and start-up support.andP;  Thedevelopment strategy must answer the questions who needs plantinformation and what type, how the information is delivered, andwhat the operator-machine interface requirements are.andP;  The systemarchitecture is established by identifying: process, company orplant requirements, I/O and interface requirements, and the bestarchitecture for the application.andP;  The 10 commandments ofautomation management are research and define development andintegration strategy, involve end user, identify I/O andinterfacing requirements, fully develop system Pandamp;ID programs, besure the plant can operate and maintain the system, maintain anopen systems architecture, establish equipment standards, be suresoftware-based systems incorporate data buffering and validitychecking, test systems from lowest level to highest, involve plantpersonnel with start-up of process system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Control SystemsManufacturingManagementControl EngineeringAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Key decision points flowchart. (chart)System block diagram. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>